                                                         Git Commands
                                                        --------------
                                                        


1. Setup Commands

Used when installing Git or setting your identity.

git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "your@email.com"
git config --list

2. Repository Creation

Create or download a repository.
git init          # Initialize a new repository
git clone <url>   # Copy an existing repository

3. Checking Repository Status

See what changes are made.
git status
git log
git log --oneline
git diff

4. Adding Files to Staging Area

Prepare files before committing.

git add file_name
git add .

5. Commit Changes

Save changes permanently / record of changes in the repository.
git commit -m "Your message"

6. Push Commands
 Push file - upload local repo. content to remote (git)repo    git push origin main   {* keychain / delete credentials

7. Clone and status
Clone - cloning a repository on your local machine             git clone <-some link > {link = repo -> code-> https-> copy}
Status - displays the state of code                            git status

8. Hidden file
Hidden files                                                   ls -a

9. Remote Repository Commands

Connect your local repo to sites like GitHub.
git remote add origin <repo_url>
git remote -v
git push origin main
git pull origin main
git fetch


10. Simple Git Workflow

git init
git add .
git commit -m "first commit"
git remote add origin URL
git push -u origin main

11. Branch Commands

Work with different versions of code.

git branch                                 # Show branches
git branch -m main                         # To rename
git branch branch_name                     # Create branch
git checkout branch_name                   # Switch branch / to navigate
git checkout -b new_branch_name            # Create new branch+ switch
git branch -d branch_name                  # Delete branch

12. Merge 
git merge branch_name      # Merge branch
git diff branch_name       # To compare commits, branches, files and more

13. Pull request
It lets you tell others about changes you've pushed to a branch in a repository on GitHub, helps to review your contributions.

git pull origin main


14. Resolving merge conflicts
When git is unable to automatically resolve differences in code between two commits.
